		<div class="post" id="post-3689403">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3689403)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3689403">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/shaggydredlocks" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1722371); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1722371&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164660" alt="Shaggydredlocks" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1722371)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/shaggydredlocks" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1722371); return false;" >Shaggydredlocks</a></span> <span class="odate time_1516636817 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">22 Jan 2018 16:00</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3689403">
									

<p>This is definitely the best submission for this series so far, being more focused and offering some genuine character interaction. My downvote fell right at the &quot;UIUseless&quot;, which elicited a heavy eyeroll.</p>
<p>Using the memey out-of-universe name which jokingly refers to a stereotype for a that group doesn't do much to build confidence that there's going to be anything much in the way of creative use of said groups, so once the Sarkites showed up, it was pretty easy to guess where it was going to go, so the story ended up being rather predictable.</p>
<p>As an aside, this was pitched as some large event that would quote &quot;rock the anomalous world&quot;, which really is certainly intriguing, but as I warned when I first heard of the concept, it's not giving that impression in the slightest. Everyone is doing exactly what one would expect each group to do. Each GoI is operating very strictly n the confines of their respective bit parts. There hasn't been any novel use or changes to speak of, and I'm feeling let down on the promise of such a massive paradigm-shifting event.</p>
<p>Hoping subsequent entries begin to surprise me.</p>

