			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3698045">
									

<blockquote>
<p>And it does not have any outstanding features of it's own. So it's basically a not very good copy.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Wouldn't it be a bad thing if it was a &quot;good copy&quot;? It's distinct enough for people to enjoy it, and if they like both, they can upvote both. They shouldn't feel pressured to like only one or the other.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>P.S. For some reason it's not the first duplication work which came recently. Ancient war elephant made by a team of very famous authors has the same problem.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&quot;Duplication&quot; implies intentional copying, which I believe is not the case of the article you're referring to here. Furthermore, there's no rule on the site that states similar works cannot exist. We have tons of dog and cat and humanoid articles, but that doesn't mean that nothing similar can ever be written ever again.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>And strangely to me has a very high rate.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Is it surprising that if lots of people like something, there are a lot of upvotes?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I just hope this is not new thread of community.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>If you feel an inherent loyalty to the first of a kind of written work and dislike all similar subsequent writings, that's your prerogative. However, the site's general rule when it comes to writing is &quot;if the audience likes it, it stays&quot;.</p>

