<blockquote>
<p>Accept for the part of Carter idea go wrong, it's very similar to one more MC&amp;D delicacy, which is also a rear egg on the plate.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Spelling errors aside, the objects may be similar, but the story is completely different. I wrote the Fossil Eggs for the History Contest, where it was in the context of the bitter rivalry between E.D. Cope and O.C. Marsh having what could have been their greatest discovery stolen by agents of Marshall, Carter and Dark.</p>
<p>This isn't ripping it off at all. The author gave more thought and care to the correspondence between those involved in MC&amp;D business than I did in Imperfectly Preserved Fossil Eggs, and is a self-contained story, where as what I wrote requires the context of an entirely different work in order to be fully understood. (P.S.: whoever runs the MC&amp;D template, please make in-text links stand out more. You can barely see them.) This stands alone in the War on All Fronts canon, and as a tale on its own.</p>
<p>To be blunt: I don't think you know what you're talking about.</p>

							</div>

								
					
